editorialDecl.p: EEBO-TCP is a partnership between the Universities of Michigan and Oxford and the publisher ProQuest to create accurately transcribed and encoded texts based on the image sets published by ProQuest via their Early English Books Online (EEBO) database (http://eebo.chadwyck.com). The general aim of EEBO-TCP is to encode one copy (usually the first edition) of every monographic English-language title published between 1473 and 1700 available in EEBO.

EEBO-TCP aimed to produce large quantities of textual data within the usual project restraints of time and funding, and therefore chose to create diplomatic transcriptions (as opposed to critical editions) with light-touch, mainly structural encoding based on the Text Encoding Initiative (http://www.tei-c.org).

The EEBO-TCP project was divided into two phases. The 25,363 texts created during Phase 1 of the project have been released into the public domain as of 1 January 2015. Anyone can now take and use these texts for their own purposes, but we respectfully request that due credit and attribution is given to their original source.
Users should be aware of the process of creating the TCP texts, and therefore of any assumptions that can be made about the data.

Text selection was based on the New Cambridge Bibliography of English Literature (NCBEL). If an author (or for an anonymous work, the title) appears in NCBEL, then their works are eligible for inclusion. Selection was intended to range over a wide variety of subject areas, to reflect the true nature of the print record of the period. In general, first editions of a works in English were prioritized, although there are a number of works in other languages, notably Latin and Welsh, included and sometimes a second or later edition of a work was chosen if there was a compelling reason to do so.

Image sets were sent to external keying companies for transcription and basic encoding. Quality assurance was then carried out by editorial teams in Oxford and Michigan. 5% (or 5 pages, whichever is the greater) of each text was proofread for accuracy and those which did not meet QA standards were returned to the keyers to be redone. After proofreading, the encoding was enhanced and/or corrected and characters marked as illegible were corrected where possible up to a limit of 100 instances per text. Any remaining illegibles were encoded as <gap>s. Understanding these processes should make clear that, while the overall quality of TCP data is very good, some errors will remain and some readable characters will be marked as illegible. Users should bear in mind that in all likelihood such instances will never have been looked at by a TCP editor.
The texts were encoded and linked to page images in accordance with level 4 of the TEI in Libraries guidelines.

Copies of the texts have been issued variously as SGML (TCP schema; ASCII text with mnemonic sdata character entities); displayable XML (TCP schema; characters represented either as UTF-8 Unicode or text strings within braces); or lossless XML (TEI P5, characters represented either as UTF-8 Unicode or TEI g elements).

Full documentation of the original data capture process is available from the Text Creation Partnership web site. All versions of the texts are now archived and freely available for download. See the TCP Download FAQ for detailed information. The TEI P5 versions are also freely available from the TCP Github repository.

div.p: A PERFECT LIST Of all such Persons as by Commission under the Great Seal of ENGLAND Are now confirmed to be.

item.hi: Justices of the Peace and Quorum,

div.p: In the several Counties, Cityes, Towns, and Liberties within England and Wales.
As they were approved of and Allowed by the late Parliament after the readmission of the secluded MEMBERS.
TOGETHER With an exact LIST of all the Commissioners for setling the Militia in England and Wales.
With an Abridgment of the Act for the MILITIA it self.

p.hi: Licensed and Entred according to Order.

div.p: LONDON, Printed by Tho. Leach, and are to be sold by Tho. Firby at his Shop at Grays-Inne Gate, 1660.
THe Reader is desired to take notice that the p • rsons hereafter named (viz.)

list.item: William Lenthall Speaker of the Parliament.

item.label: Lords Commissioners of the great Seal of England.

list.item: Richard Newdigate Lord Chief Justice of the Upper Bench.

div.p: Are all of them inserted into the several Commissions of the peace for all the several and respective Counties, Cities, Towns, and Liberties in England and Wales, hereafter named.

And also that all such Persons whose names (in the Catalogue of Justices of the Peace) are marked with the letter [m] are by Act of Parliament dated the 12th. of March Ann. Dom. 1659. appointed also to be Commissioners of the Militia, in the several Counties, Cities, Townes, and Places where they are so marked, the rest of the Commissioners of the Militia in that Act, named (who are not in the Commission of the Peace) are placed together at the end of every such Catalogue of Justices of each County

div.head: The Copy of the Commissions, delivered to the Officers of the Militia by the Council of State. By the Council of State appointed by Authority of Parliament.
div.p: BY Vertue of Authority to Us given by the Parliament of the Common-wealth of England, We do constitute and appoint you _____ And you are hereby constituted and appointed _____ of that Militia _____ of _____ in the Regiment of Colonel _____ raised, or to be raised within the _____ by vertue of an Act of the late Parliament, published the 12 day of March, 1659. Entituled, An Act for setling the Militia within England and Wales: For the ends and purposes expressed in the said Act; You are therefore to take into your charge and care the said _____ as _____ thereof, and duely to exercise the Inferiour Officers and Souldiers of the same, in Arms, and to use your best care and endeavour to keep them in good Order and Discipline; Commanding them to obey you as their _____ And you are likewise to observe and follow such Orders and Directions as you shall from time to time receive from the Parliament, the Council of State appointed by authority of Parliament, or the Commissioners for the Militia for the _____ And you are also to obey your Superiour Officers, according to the Discipline of War, in pursuance of the Trust hereby reposed in you, and of your duty to the Common-wealth.

div.head: More of the Militia for all North-Wales.
Commissioners of the Militia for the City of London.
An Abridgement of the Act for setling the Militia within England and VVales Monday, March the 12th. 1659.
div.p: Ordered by the Parliament that this Act be forthwith Printed and Published.

BEe it Enacted by this present Parliament, and it is hereby Declared, that an Act of Parliament bearing date the six & twentieth day of July 1659. and all other Acts and Orders concerning the Misitia of the respective Counties in England and Wales, and the Powers and Commissions thereby given and granted, and all Men, Money, Horses, or Arms levyed by virtue thereof, do from henceforth cease and determine, and are hereby vacated and made void

And it is hereby further Enacted that the Persons hereafter mentioned, shall be, and are hereby appointed Commissioners of the Militia in the respective Counties in England and Wales, and Town of Barwick upon Tweed.

The Commissioners are most of them taken out of the List of the Justices of the Peace in each several County, and are marked in that List with the Letter (m) and such others of the Commissioners of the Militia as are not in the Catalogue of the Justices, are added and expressed at the end of every such List of Justices in each several County, City, and Town; So that all the Commissioners of the Militia are herein before fully named.

Which said Commissioners, or any five or more of them in the several places where they are named Commissioners, have power to meet together, and to call before them all such persons as are fit and meet to bear Arms, and to cause them to be sufficiently Armed, Arrayed, and Weaponed, and to put them into Regiments, Troops, and Companies, and to conduct or cause them to be conducted into any place or places as well within, as out of such County, according to such directions as they shall receive from the Parliament, or Council of Stare, for suppressing of all Insurrections or Invasions; And shall have power to present to the Council of State for their approbation, the names of such persons (observing the qualifications therein mentioned) as they shall think fit to be Collonells, Lieuetenant, Collonels Majors, Captains, and other Commission Officers of such Forces so to be
raised, which Officers being so approved, shall have Commissions signed by the Council of State, or any 9 or more of them, and thereby have power to train and conduct all such persons so to be armed, according to the directions and to the intents and purposes aforesaid.

And for the providing Horses, Arms and other necessaries for the arming and weaponing of such Forces, and for defraying incident charges, It is further Enacted that the said Commissioners or any five or more of them within their several Jurisdictions, have hereby full power and authority to charge any person with horse and arms in the same County or place where his, her, or their estates lye, provided, no person be charged with a horse & arms, unlesse he or she have five hundred pounds yearly revenue, or an estate of six thousand pounds in goods, mony, or other estate equivalent thereunto, and so proportionably as the said Commissioners shall think fit, nor any person charged to find a foot Souldier and arms, unless he have a personall estate of five hundred pounds, or a yearly revenue of forty pounds, and so proportionably for a greater or lesser revenue or estate, it shall be lawfull for the Commissioners or any five or more of them, to joyn two three or more persons together in the charge for providing of horse and arms as aforesaid as shall appeare to them to be most beneficiall for the service of the Nation.

Provided, that no person who hath not 100 l. a year in Lands Tenements or Hereditaments Leasehold or Coppyhold, shall be compelled to contribute towards finding a horse with arms, and that no person who hath not fifteen pounds a year, in Lands Tenements
&c. or a personall estate worth 200 l. shall not be compellable to con • ribute in finding a Foot arms as aforesaid; And the said Commissioners or any five or more of them have power to examine complaints, and upon oath (which they have power to administer) to give redresse as there shall be cause.

And be it further Enacted that the said Commissioners or any five or more of them, in their respective Counties and places, shall direct and req • ire all pe • sons so charged as aforesaid to allow 2 s. per diem to such horsemen; and 1 s. per diem to every such foot Souldier for every day they shall be absent by occasion of muster or exercise; And for the furnishing such forces with Drums, Colours, Ammunition, and other emergencies, the said Commissioners, or any five or more of them, (whereof none to be a Commission Officer) shall h • ve power to impose a rate upon their several Coun • ies, not to exceed in the whole one moneth ass ••• m • nt, at the rate of 35000 l. per moneth; which monies are to be assessed, collected and paid a • the Parliament or Co • ncil of State shall from time to time direct unto such Collectors and Treasurers as the said Commissioners shall appoint, under such pena • ties, and by such ways and means, as in the Act for 35000 l. per mensem are prescribed: And in •• se there shal be any sudden occasion to 〈◊〉 out s •• h Souldiers into actual Service, the per
〈…〉 so ch • rged, as aforesaid, are to furnish their men 〈◊〉
• ay in hand, not exceeding one months pay, as 〈…〉 ll • e by the Commissioners, or any five, or more 〈◊〉 them directed for re-payment wherof, & for satisfaction of such Officers as shall be with their Souldiers
in such said actual service, not exceeding one moneth, as aforesaid, the Parliament doth hereby declare, the same shall be paid out of the publique Treasury, and if they shall be continued longer in actual service, the like course shall be taken for the payment of such Officers and Souldiers, as is for the establish'd Army.

And be it further enacted, That the said Commissioners, or any five, ot more of them, upon the marching of any such forces, (allowing 6 pence a mile outward only) may charge Carts, Wag • ons, and Horses, for the carrying of Powder, Bullets, and other materials, and may imprison Muttineers and disordered persons, or such as shall neglect their duties at dayes of Trayning or Mustering, and if drawn upon actual service, to be subject during that time, to such rules and orders as are mentioned in the general instructions for regulation of the Army.

And be it further enacted, that such persons as shall refuse or neglect (by the time appointed by the said Commissioners) to provide such Horse, Horses, Arms, or other furniture, o • to pay su • h Sum or Sums of Money towards the providing and furnishing as aforesaid, that then the said Commissioners may inflict a penalty upon such persons not exceeding 20 l. and also by Warrant commit such persons to prison, there to remain without Bail or Mainprize, untill they shall conform thereunto, and pay such penalty, or else by like Warrant, to levy the value of such Horses, Arms, or Furniture, and such penalties so inflicted by s • le of the Goods of such Refusers or Neglecters, rendring the overplus to the party distrained (all charges first deducted.)

And be it further enacted, that if any person imbezel the Horse, Arms, or Furniture, wherewith he is intrusted, the said Commissioners may imprison such persons till they make satisfaction; and if any person shall not appear complearly furnished with the Horse, Arms, and other Furniture, wherewith he is intrusted, at the beat of Drum, sound of Trumpet, or other Summons, that then, and so often, the said Commissioners (if the default be in such person or persons so intrusted) nay imprison such person five dayes without Bail or Mainprize, or inflict the penalty, if a Horseman, not exceeding 20 s. and if a Footman, not exceeding 10 s. to be paid down without delay; And if any person so charged as aforesaid, shall upon such Summons refuse to deliver his Horse, Arms, or other furniture, the Commissioners may inflict the penalty of 5 l. upon such Refuser, to be levyed by sale of his Goods; And the said Commissioners or any three of them, may examine any person upon O • th, touching the ability of such persons so to be charged and assessed, and of all misdemeanors tending to the hindrance of the service aforesaid.

And for the more speedy execution hereof; Be it further enacted, that the said Commissioners may as often as they shall think fit appoint general meetings, and at such meetings appoint one or more Treasurer or Treasurers, Check or Checks, for the receiving and paying of all such monies as by vertue hereof shall be levyed, of all which receits and disbursements, the said Treasurers and Receivers, Check or Checks, are every six months to give their accompts in writing to the Parliament if then Sitting, and in the intervals to the Council
of State, or whom they shall appoint to receive them.

And be it further enacted, that any five or more of the said Commissioners, may Summon all and every such person or persons who are possessed of any Sum or Sums of money, Horses, Arms, or Ammunition, relating to the said Militia, and so require them to give a just accompt thereof upon Oath, and to pay and deliver all such Sums of money, Horses, &c. remaining in their hands, to such persons as the Commissioners hereby appointed, or any five or more of them shall appoint, and in case of non-payment, to levy the same by distresse and sale as aforesaid, and for want of distresse, to imprison their persons till they conform; All which monyes so to be levyed and received, are to be imployed for carrying on the said service, and at such general meetings, the said Commissioners are to divide themselves into such numbers and divisions, as may be most expeditious for the service.

And for the better securing of the peace of the Nation, the said Commissioners or any five or more of them, may by Warrant under their Hands and Seals imploy such persons as they shall think fit, of which the Constable or his Deputy within their precinct to be one, in the day time to search for, and seize all Arms in the custody of any Popish Recusant that hath been in Arms against the Parliament, or any other whom the Commi • sioners shall Judge dange • ous to the Peace of the Nation, and to secure such Arms for the use of the Commonwealth, or with them to Arm such well-affected persons as they shall think fit, and the persons so imployed may enter into the House or Lodging of
any such person and there seize and take away what Arms they shall find, and to give an accompt thereof to the said Commissioners.

And all high Constables, Petty Constables, and other Officers, are to be aiding and assisting to the said • ommissioners in the Execution of the premises, and for so doing, shall be saved harmlesse by Authority of Parliament.

And be it further enacted, that where any person shall be charged to find a Horse, Horses, and Arms in such County, City, or Place where he doth not reside; That then the Commissioners shall send notice of such charge to the Servant of such person there residing, or in case he have no such Servant there, then to the Tenant or Tenants of such person so charged, who are required to Convey the same with all speed to their Master or Landlord respectively, and within such time as the Commissioners shall appoint, bring an accompt of their Master or Landlords answer to the said Commissioners; And if the Landlord shall refuse or neglect to provide what he is so charged with, that then the Tenant or Tenants, shall be compelled to do what the Landlord ought to have done; And upon the like neglect of the Tenants, that then, and upon every such defauls, the said Commissioners may by Warrant levy all such penalties, as by this Act are appointed by distresse and sale of the Offenders Goods.

And it is hereby further ordained, that all such Tenant or Tenants shall defaulk all such Sums of mony as they shall disburse for their Landlords by reason of distresse, or otherwise for any default in manner aforesaid o • t of the next rent due to his Landlord,
any Contract to the contrary notwithstanding, and the said Tenant or Tenants shall be indempnified for so doing by Authority of Parliament, unlesse the Landlord shall within a month make it appear to the Commissioners that the default and penalties were occasioned by the neglect of such Tenant or Tenants.

Provided alwayes that where any person shall be charged with a horse and arms, and shall not by the Commissioners be suffered to put Riders upon them, or to have his arms born by such person as he shall send in, that then the said Commissioners are to take care that immediately after the service ended such horses be redelivered to such persons as sent them in, unlesse such horses be lost in actual service, and that their arms be detained in such hands as the Commissioners thought fit should ride and bear the same, to the end they may be in readiness for future service, as well as others.

Provided always that no person shall either ride a horse or carry arms in this service, that hath been in arms against the Parliament or aided or assisted therein, unlesse he hath since manifested his good affections to the Parliament. Provided also that no person shall be employed in this service as a Commission Officer, but such or the Sons of such who have adhered to the Parliaments cause, unless such Sons have shewed their disaffection to the Parliaments cause.

Provided that if any Person shall be charged with a horse and arms, in the County or place wher his orher chief Mansion, house is for his or her whole estate, that then upon certificate that such person is so assessed for his whole estate in the said
County or place, such person shall be discharged from any assessement elsewhere, where his estate lyeth.

Provided that no Commissioner nor Commissioned Officer shall exercise any the powers or authorities herein mentioned, or do any thing in pursuance thereof, untill in the presence of five or more of the said Commissioners, he shall first acknowledge in these words following (to wit)
div.q: I do acknowledge and declare, that the War undertaken by both houses of Parliament, in their defence against the Forces raised in the name of the late King, was just and lawfull, and that Magistracy and Ministry are the ordinances of God.
div.closer: Monday March the 12th. 1659. Ordered that this Act be Printed and published.
